However, while over 60% of the population is affiliated with the three Christian denominations (Seventh Day Adventist, Jehovah's Witnesses, and Quakers), Guyana also has a Muslim minority and Hindus. As a result of strong religious pushback, over the last decade Government has either refused to pass proactive abortion regulations or has delayed any abortion regulation proposal led by Guyana Feminist Movement and Guyanese women’s organization such as GLOWE. The Christian Leaders Initiative (CLI), a religious coalition is the main body to blame for the continued denial of women’s rights to health care. They push forward their strong anti-rights campaign in efforts to maintain control over Guyana.

In life, women and children have no say, for it is man’s duty to ensure a secure future for his family. The status quo has had an enormous effect on the effect of women’s rights, for men were traditionally in decision- making roles using their positions of power to oppress women; a great many men make decisions based on a sense of duty to be self-sufficient while struggling to make ends meet. While the situation has been improving over the past decade, it still remains to be seen the extent of progress that will be achieved. These factors ultimately make Guyana a major gender-gap-country, scoring 0.535 according to the World Bank’s Gender Indices.
